<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:lang="en-US" xml:id="trigonometry-polar-coordinates">
  <title>Polar Coordinates</title>

  <paragraphs>
    <title>Polar Coordinates</title>
    <p></p>
    <p>
      When graphing in two-dimensions, the most common way we identify points in the plane is with the use of rectangular coordinates <mdash/> i.e. by the ordered pair <m>(x,y)</m> (or whatever variables are in use).  In this section we talk about an alternate strategy for identifying points in the plane <mdash/> with the use of polar coordinates.
    </p>
    <p>
      In the polar plane, the point we call the origin in the rectangular plane is called <term>the pole</term>.  A point in the plane, <m>P</m>, identified using <term>polar coordinates</term> has the form <m>(r,\theta)</m> where <m>r</m> is the signed distance from the pole to <m>P</m> and <m>\theta</m> is an angle that when drawn in standard position has a terminal side that passes either through the pole and <m>P</m> or through the pole and the direction opposite of <m>P</m>.
    </p>
    <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

      <p>
        The polar plane is shown in <xref ref="trigonometry-polar-coordinates-figure-1">Figure</xref>.  One polar ordered pair that plots to point labeled <m>A</m> is <m>\left(4,\frac{\pi}{6}\right)</m>.  One polar ordered pair that plots to point labeled <m>B</m> is <m>\left(3,\frac{17\pi}{12}\right)</m>.  Unlike the rectangular plane, however, neither of these ordered pairs are unique.  In fact, for each point there are an unlimited number of ordered pairs that plot to that single point.
      </p>

      <figure xml:id="trigonometry-polar-coordinates-figure-1">
        <caption>The Polar Plane</caption>
        <image>
          <description>
            A graph of the polar plane.  There are six concentric circles centered at the pole.  The circles have radii of <m>1</m>, <m>2</m>, <m>3</m>, <m>4</m>, <m>5</m>, and <m>6</m>.  There are 24 spoke emanating from the pole, each consecutive pair of spokes covering one twenty-fourth of a revolution which is equivalent to <m>\frac{\pi}{12}</m>.  The spokes are labeled <m>0</m>, <m>\frac{\pi}{12}</m>, <m>\frac{\pi}{6}</m>, <m>\frac{\pi}{4}</m>, <m>\frac{\pi}{3}</m>, <m>\frac{5\pi}{6}</m>, <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m>, ..., <m>\frac{7\pi}{4}</m>, <m>\frac{11\pi}{6}</m>, and <m>\frac{23\pi}{12}</m>.  There is a large dot labeled <m>A</m> at the point where the circle of radius <m>4</m> intersects the terminal arm of the angle labeled <m>\frac{\pi}{6}</m>.  There is a large dot labeled <m>B</m> at the point where the circle of radius <m>3</m> intersects the terminal arm of the angle labeled <m>\frac{17\pi}{12}</m>.
          </description>
          <latex-image>
              <![CDATA[
