    </sidebyside>
    <p>
      When drawn in standard position, any two angles whose difference is an integer multiple of <m>2\pi</m> are coterminal.  One repercussion of this  is that each of the following polar ordered pairs will plot to <m>A</m>.
      <me>...,\,\left(4,-\frac{11\pi}{6}\right),\,\left(4,\frac{\pi}{6}\right),\,\left(4,\frac{13\pi}{6}\right),\,...</me>
      But these aren't the only polar ordered pairs that plot to <m>A</m>.  When the value of <m>r</m> is negative, we plot the point using the fact that <m>(r,\theta)</m> and <m>(-r,\theta+\pi)</m> plot to the same point.
    </p>
    <p>
      So, for example suppose that we wanted to plot the point <m>\left(-4,\frac{7\pi}{6}\right)</m>.  This will plot in the same location as the point derived below.
      <me>\left(4,\frac{7\pi}{6}+\pi\right)=\left(4,\frac{13\pi}{6}\right)</me>
      Because <m>\left(4,\frac{13\pi}{6}\right)</m> has already been identified as an ordered pair that plots to <m>A</m>, it must be the case that <m>\left(-4,\frac{7\pi}{6}\right)</m> also plots to <m>A</m>.
    </p>
    <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

      <p>
        One way that you can think about negative values of <m>r</m> is to image the positive <m>x</m>-axis being rotated to the <m>\theta</m>-coordinate of the polar ordered pair.  This is illustrated in <xref ref="trigonometry-polar-coordinates-figure-2">Figure</xref> for a <m>\theta</m> value of <m>\frac{7\pi}{6}</m>.  The positive values of <m>r</m> emanate from the pole in the direction of <m>\frac{7\pi}{6}</m> and the negative values of <m>r</m> emanate from the pole in the opposite direction of <m>\frac{7\pi}{6}</m>, i.e. in the direction of <m>\frac{7\pi}{6}+\pi</m>.
      </p>

