  <paragraphs>
    <title>Converting Between Polar Coordinates and Rectangular Coordinates.</title>
    <p></p>
    <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

      <p>
        There are several mathematical relationships between the labeled parts of the right triangle shown in <xref ref="trigonometry-polar-coordinates-figure-4">Figure</xref>.  Three notable relationships come from trigonometry and are stated below.
        <me>\sin(\theta)=\frac{y}{r}</me>
        <me>\cos(\theta)=\frac{x}{r}</me>
        <me>\tan(\theta)=\frac{y}{x}</me>
      </p>

      <figure xml:id="trigonometry-polar-coordinates-figure-4">
        <caption>Conversion Between Polar and Rectangular Coordinates</caption>
        <image>
          <description>
            A right triangle drawn in Quadrant one with one of the acute angle's vertex at the origin/pole.  The bottom side of the triangle is labeled <m>x</m>.  The side opposite the origin/pole is labeled <m>y</m>.  The hypotenuse is labeled <m>r</m>.  The angle at the origin/pole is labeled <m>\theta</m>.
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis} [axis equal image,
                            xmin=-0.9,xmax=1.8,
                            ymin=-0.9,ymax=1.8]
                \addplot [domain=0:50,samples=100,color=black,line width=1pt,-] ({0.2*cos(x)},{0.2*sin(x)}) node[pos=0.75,right] {$\theta$};
                \addplot [domain=0:1.028,line width=1.5pt,-,color=blue] {tan(50)*x} node[pos=0.4,above left] {$r$};
                \addplot [domain=0:1.028,line width=1.5pt,-,color=blue] {0} node[pos=0.5,below] {$x$}; 
                \addplot[interval,blue,ultra thick,-] coordinates {(1.028,-0.01) (1.028,1.226)} node[pos=0.5,right] {$y$}; 
                \addplot[interval,black,thick,-] coordinates {(0.928,0) (0.928,0.1)};
                \addplot [domain=0.928:1.028,line width=1pt,-,color=black] {0.1};                   
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

    </sidebyside>
    <p>
      A fourth notable relationship comes from the Pythagorean theorem.
      <me>r^2=x^2+y^2</me>
      We can use these relationships to convert between polar coordinates and rectangular coordinates.
    </p> 
    <p>
      When converting from polar coordinates to rectangular coordinates we use the following two formulas.
    </p>
    <sidebyside widths ="47% 47%" margins="0%">

      <p>
        <me>x=r\cos(\theta)</me>
      </p>

      <p>
        <me>y=r\sin(\theta)</me>
      </p>

    </sidebyside>
    <p>
      When converting from rectangular coordinates to polar coordinates we use the following two formulas.
    </p>
    <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

      <p>
        <me>r=\sqrt{x^2+y^2}</me>
      </p>

      <p>
        <me>\tan(\theta)=\frac{y}{x}</me>
      </p>

    </sidebyside>
    <p>
      When applying the formula <m>\tan(\theta)=\frac{y}{x}</m>, we need to use caution in the use of the inverse tangent key.  That key will return a correct value for <m>\theta</m> if and only <m>\theta</m> terminates in either Quadrant I or Quadrant IV.  If <m>\theta</m> terminates in Quadrant II or Quadrant III and you need to use your inverse tangent key, the most straight forward thing to do is to find the reference angle, <m>\theta^{\,\prime}</m>, in the following way.
      <me>\theta^{\,\prime}=\tan^{-1}\left(\abs{\frac{y}{x}}\right)</me>
      Then subtract or add <m>\theta^{\,\prime}</m> to <m>\pi</m> dependent, respectively, upon whether the point lies in Quadrant II or Quadrant III.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Convert each of the following ordered pairs from rectangular coordinates to polar coordinates.
          <ol label="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\left(12,\frac{5\pi}{3}\right)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\left(-20,-\frac{5\pi}{4}\right)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The formulas for converting from polar coordinates to rectangular coordinates can be applied in a passive manner <mdash/> that is, we don't need to worry about reaching a false conclusion by careless application of the inverse tangent function.  Let's proceed.
          <ol label="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                <md>
                  <mrow>\left(12\cos\left(\frac{5\pi}{3}\right),12\sin\left(\frac{5\pi}{3}\right)\right)\amp=\left(12 \cdot \frac{1}{2},12 \cdot -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\right)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=(6,-6\sqrt{3})</mrow>
                </md>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <md>
                  <mrow>\left(-20\cos\left(-\frac{5\pi}{4}\right),-20\sin\left(-\frac{5\pi}{4}\right)\right)\amp=\left(-20 \cdot -\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2},-20 \cdot \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\right)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=(10\sqrt{2},-10\sqrt{2})</mrow>
                </md>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Convert each of the following ordered pairs from rectangular coordinates to polar coordinates.  In all cases state a positive value for <m>r</m> and choose a value for <m>\theta</m> that falls on the interval <m>[0,2\pi)</m>.  For parts (a) and (b) state exact values for both <m>r</m> and <m>\theta</m>.  For parts (c) and (d), state an exact value for <m>r</m> but round the value of <m>\theta</m> to the nearest thousandth. 
          <ol label="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(4,4\sqrt{3})</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(-7\sqrt{2},-7\sqrt{2})</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(3,-4)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(-5,12)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol label="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                Let's begin by determining the value of <m>r</m>.
                <md>
                  <mrow>r\amp=\sqrt{x^2+y^2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\sqrt{4^2+(4\sqrt{3})^2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\sqrt{64}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=8</mrow>
                </md>
              </p>
              <p>
                To determine the value of <m>\theta</m>, we need to find the solution to <m>\tan(\theta)=\frac{y}{x}</m> that lies in Quadrant I and falls between <m>0</m> and <m>2\pi</m>.
                <md>
                  <mrow>\tan(\theta)=\frac{y}{x}\,\,\amp\Longrightarrow\,\,\tan(\theta)=\frac{4\sqrt{3}}{4}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp\Longrightarrow\,\,\tan(\theta)=\sqrt{3}</mrow>
                </md>
                The solution to the last equation that satisfies the stated requirements is <m>\frac{\pi}{3}</m>.
              </p>
              <p>
                In conclusion, a polar equivalent of the rectangular ordered pair <m>(4,4\sqrt{3})</m> is 
                <me>\left(8,\frac{\pi}{3}\right).</me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                We begin by determining the value of <m>r</m>.
                <md>
                  <mrow>r\amp=\sqrt{x^2+y^2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\sqrt{\left(-7\sqrt{2}\right)^2+\left(-7\sqrt{2}\right)^2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\sqrt{196}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=14</mrow>
                </md>
                To determine the value of <m>\theta</m>, we need to find the solution to the equation <m>\tan(\theta)=\frac{y}{x}</m> that lies in Quadrant III and falls between <m>0</m> and <m>2\pi</m>.
                <md>
                  <mrow>\tan(\theta)=\frac{y}{x}\amp\,\,\Longrightarrow\,\,\tan(\theta)=\frac{-7\sqrt{2}}{-7\sqrt{2}}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp\Longrightarrow\,\,\tan(\theta)=1</mrow>
                </md>
                The solution to the last equation that meets the specified conditions is <m>\frac{5\pi}{4}</m>.
              </p>
              <p>
                In conclusion, a polar equivalent of the rectangular ordered pair <m>(-7\sqrt{2},-7\sqrt{2})</m> is
                <me>\left(14,\frac{5\pi}{4}\right).</me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                A good place to start is to determine the value of <m>r</m>.
                <md>
                  <mrow>r\amp=\sqrt{x^2+y^2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\sqrt{3^2+(-4)^2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\sqrt{25}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=5</mrow>
                </md>
                Let's move on to <m>\theta</m>.  We need to determine the solution to <m>\tan(\theta)=\frac{y}{x}</m> that lies in Quadrant IV and falls on the interval <m>[0,2\pi)</m>.
                <md>
                  <mrow>\tan(\theta)=\frac{y}{x}\,\,\amp\Longrightarrow\,\,\tan(\theta)=\frac{-4}{3}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp\Longrightarrow\,\,\tan(\theta)=-\frac{4}{3}</mrow>
                </md>
                This last equation is not one for which we know an exact solution.  However, because the range of the inverse tangent function is <m>\left(-\frac{\pi}{2},\frac{\pi}{2}\right)</m> and the point we're analyzing lies in Quadrant IV, we can use <m>\tan^{-1}\left(-\frac{4}{3}\right)</m> to directly determine an angle that could be used in the polar ordered pair.
                <me>\tan^{-1}\left(-\frac{4}{3}\right)\approx -0.927</me>
                A mentioned, in general this would be a fine value for <m>\theta</m>, but the problem specified that we need to use a value that falls between <m>0</m> and <m>2\pi</m>.  We can find the specified value by adding <m>2\pi</m> to the value the calculator returned and do so below.
                <md>
                  <mrow>\theta\approx -.927+2\pi</mrow>
                  <mrow>\approx 5.356</mrow>
                </md>
              </p>
              <p>
                To sum up, one polar equivalent to the rectangular ordered pair <m>(3,-4)</m> is approximately
                <me>(5,5.536).</me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Once again, let's begin by determining the value of <m>r</m>.
                <md>
                  <mrow>r\amp=\sqrt{x^2+y^2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\sqrt{(-5)^2+12^2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\sqrt{169}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=13</mrow>
                </md>
                Determination of <m>\theta</m> requires us to figure out the solution to <m>\tan(\theta)=\frac{y}{x}</m> that lies in Quadrant II and falls between <m>0</m> and <m>2\pi</m>.
                <md>
                  <mrow>\tan(\theta)=\frac{y}{x}\,\,\amp\Longrightarrow\,\,\tan(\theta)=\frac{12}{-5}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp\Longrightarrow\,\,\tan(\theta)=-\frac{12}{5}</mrow>
                </md>
                We do not know an exact solution for the last equation, so we will need to use technology to find an approximate solution.  Unfortunately, <m>\theta</m> needs to point into Quadrant II, and technology will give us a solution in Quadrant IV.  Let's use <m>\tan^{-1}\left(\frac{12}{5}\right)</m> to determine the reference angle for <m>\theta</m> and proceed from there.
                <md>
                  <mrow>\theta^{\,\prime}\amp=\tan^{-1}\left(\frac{12}{5}\right)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp\approx 1.176</mrow>
                </md>
                Because <m>\theta</m> lies in Quadrant II, we need to subtract <m>\theta^{\,\prime}</m> from <m>\pi</m> to determine its (approximate) value.
                <me>\pi-1.176\approx 1.966</me>
                We conclude by stating that an approximate polar equivalent of the rectangular ordered pair <m>(-5,12)</m> is
                <me>(13,1.966).</me>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>

        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

  </paragraphs>
  <paragraphs>
    <title>Graphing Polar Functions</title>
    <p></p>
    <p>
      Polar functions are generally stated in the format <m>r=f(\theta)</m>.  Because we state polar ordered pairs using the format <m>(r,\theta)</m>, it follows that unlike rectangular ordered pairs, in polar ordered pairs the second coordinate is generally the independent variable and the first coordinate is the dependent variable.
    </p>
    <p>
      Let's consider the polar function <m>r=4\cos(\theta)</m>.  If we want to plot a graph of this function, a good place to start would be with a table of values.  The table I'm going to create is going to contain values of <m>\theta</m> that increase from <m>0</m> up through <m>\frac{11\pi}{6}</m>.  The points need to be connected in a counterclockwise fashion in the order in which they appeared.  This can sometimes get a little confusing when the value of <m>r</m> turns negative.  For this reason I'm going to assign names to the points to help us recall the order.  This is done in <xref ref="trigonometry-polar-coordinates-table-1">Figure</xref>.  I went ahead and used my calculator to get approximate values for <m>r</m> in order to facilitate point plotting.
