    <p>
      We can now replace <m>r^2</m> with <m>x^2+y^2</m> and <m>r\cos(\theta)</m> with <m>x</m>, resulting in the following.
      <me>x^2+y^2=4x</me>
      Let's move the linear term to the left side of the equation and complete the square and then pause to see if the mystery has been solved.
      <md>
        <mrow>x^2+y^2\amp=4x</mrow>
        <mrow>x^2-4x+y^2\amp=0</mrow>
        <mrow>x^2-4x\addright{4}+y^2\amp=0\addright{4}</mrow>
        <mrow>(x-2)^2+y^2\amp=4</mrow>
      </md>
      This last equation is indeed the equation of a circle with a radius of <m>2</m> centered at the rectangular point <m>(2,0)</m>.  So there you have it.
    </p>

