  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Convert each polar equation to a rectangular equation to determine the appearance of the graph of the polar equation.
        <ol label="a">
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>r=7</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>r=3\sec(\theta)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\theta=\frac{\pi}{3}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol label="a">
          <li>
            <p>
              We begin by squaring both sides of the equation resulting in
              <me>r^2=49.</me>
              Replacing <m>r^2</m> with <m>x^2+y^2</m> give us
              <me>x^2+y^2=49.</me>
              This rectangular equation graphs to a circle centered at the origin with a radius of <m>7</m>.  So <m>r=7</m> is a circle centered at the pole with a radius of <m>7</m> which makes sense as any point with an <m>r</m>-coordinate of <m>7</m> lies on that circle.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <md>
                <mrow>r=3\sec(\theta)\,\,\amp\Longrightarrow\,\,r=\frac{3}{\cos(\theta)}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp\Longrightarrow\,\,r\cos(\theta)=3</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp\Longrightarrow\,\,x=3</mrow>
              </md>
              From this last equation we can conclude that <m>r=3\sec(\theta)</m> graphs to a vertical line that passes through the polar point <m>(3,0)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <md>
                <mrow>\theta=\frac{\pi}{3}\,\,\amp\Longrightarrow\,\,\tan(\theta)=\tan\left(\frac{\pi}{3}\right)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp\Longrightarrow\,\,\frac{y}{x}=\sqrt{3}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp\Longrightarrow\,\,y=\sqrt{3}x</mrow>
              </md>
              So <m>\theta=\frac{\pi}{3}</m> graphs to a line through the pole that has a rectangular slope of <m>\sqrt{3}</m>. This makes sense as any point with a <m>\theta</m>-coordinate of <m>\frac{\pi}{3}</m> lies on that line.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  </paragraphs>

